🚀 **Day 14/90 – Linux & DevOps Challenge**

Today I focused on **Linux Networking Fundamentals**, one of the core skills every DevOps engineer needs.

### 📚 Topics I Learned

* 🌐 OSI Model vs TCP/IP Model
* 📡 IP Address and Network Basics
* 🔄 TCP vs UDP
* 🔍 DNS (Domain Name System)
* 🔒 HTTP vs HTTPS

### 💻 Hands-on Commands Practiced

* `hostname -I`
* `ip addr`
* `ping`
* `traceroute`
* `ss -tulpn`
* `dig`
* `nslookup`
* `curl -I`
* `netstat`

### 🛠️ What I Practiced

* Checked my system's IP address
* Tested internet connectivity using `ping`
* Verified DNS resolution
* Checked listening ports and active services
* Tested HTTP responses with `curl`
* Learned how to troubleshoot basic network issues step by step

### 🎯 Key Takeaways

* Networking is the backbone of Linux and DevOps.
* Understanding TCP/IP and DNS makes troubleshooting much easier.
* Tools like `ping`, `ss`, `curl`, and `dig` provide quick insights into connectivity and service health.
* A structured troubleshooting approach helps identify problems faster.

Every day I'm building a stronger foundation in Linux and DevOps by learning both the concepts and the practical commands.

Looking forward to the next challenge! 🚀🐧

